// The destruction hook (destruction.md §5). At the end of an owner's scope the
// compiler runs `drop` through a `&mut self` loan, then destroys the fields
// afterward (reverse field order) — so a value cannot resurrect itself. `Drop`
// is implementable ONLY for a `resource` type: destruction without move
// discipline is exactly the double-close bug. `drop` is synchronous in v1;
// cancel owned tasks via an `OwnedNursery`. A resource without a `Drop` impl is
// still legal — containment alone moves it and drops its fields.
//
// (The compiler-inserted teardown is a later slice; this declares the surface.)
trait Drop {
	fun drop(&mut self);
}

// Early teardown (destruction.md §5/§6): move a value into `drop` to destroy it
// at this (immediate) scope end, instead of waiting for the owner's scope to
// close. The call is rewritten at each site by the concrete argument type — for
// a resource it lowers directly to that type's destructor; for plain data it is
// a no-op that merely consumes the argument for its effects. There is no public
// `close()` to keep in sync with a destructor; `drop(x)` IS the early form. The
// `own` parameter makes the argument a move (R3), so the value is spent here.
fun drop<T>(own value: T) {}
